          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the pastry and shape the case",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bring the lard and water to a rolling boil. Pour into the flour and salt and beat quickly with a wooden spoon until a smooth, pliable dough forms. Work while warm. Set aside a third of the dough for the lid. Press the remaining dough into a 20 cm springform tin or round a floured jar placed on a baking tray, working the pastry up the sides to a 1 cm thickness. The sides must be even and tall enough to contain the filling.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fill and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 200°C conventional. Mix the pork, bacon, salt, pepper, mace, thyme, and anchovies together thoroughly. Pack tightly into the pastry case. Roll the reserved pastry into a lid and press it firmly onto the case, crimping the edges tightly to seal. Cut a small hole in the centre of the lid. Brush with beaten egg. Bake for 30 minutes at 200°C, then reduce to 170°C and bake for a further 60 minutes. The internal temperature of the filling should reach 75°C on an instant-read thermometer. Cool in the tin for 30 minutes, then remove and cool completely.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pour the jelly",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Warm the chicken stock to a simmer. Squeeze the soaked gelatine dry and stir into the hot stock until fully dissolved. Allow to cool until it is the temperature of warm tap water but still liquid. Using a small funnel or a jug with a thin spout, pour the jelly through the hole in the lid. You will hear it filling the air gap inside. Refrigerate overnight until completely set before cutting.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
